    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The UnitOfAssurance for Morrison COU1 (CPB hemolysis, MRL 5) is accepted based on the following structured evidence summary: (1) All 13 credibility factors have been assessed at MRL 5 rigor; all achievedLevels meet or exceed requiredLevels with no shortfalls. (2) NIH predictions are within 9.7% relative error of experimental measurements across all five COU operating points, well within the 15% acceptance criterion, with the validation comparison norm |E| < u_val confirming no detectable model inadequacy signal above measurement noise. (3) The global Sobol sensitivity analysis (4096 samples, 11 inputs) demonstrates that prediction uncertainty is dominated by tip clearance and hemolysis power-law coefficients, both of which are characterized with primary measurements and propagated to 95% prediction intervals that conservatively envelope experimental observations. (4) The validation hierarchy spans unit-physics (MMS, FDA benchmark), component (pressure rise), and system-level (NIH) validation, providing a complete evidential chain. (5) Software quality, use error controls, and independent reproduction checks provide high confidence that the reported predictions are free from implementation and execution errors. (6) The operating envelope and applicability constraints are clearly bounded and all validation activities fall within these bounds. The credibility evidence is sufficient to support the regulatory claim that the CFD model can reliably identify worst-case hemolysis operating conditions for this Class II CPB device at the required MRL 5 level of rigor.",
